# [CATS](../wg/cats.html)

## Summary
The CATS (Computing-Aware Traffic Steering) working group met at IETF 125 to review the progress of its core framework, metrics definitions, and several foundational drafts covering OAM, security, and data models. The chairs noted that the core framework has moved to the IESG, and the working group is now focusing on metrics and protocol applicability. Significant discussion was held regarding the applicability of CATS to optical networks and specialized AI workloads.

## Key Discussion Points

### Working Group Document Updates

*   **01. Chairs Slides** ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cats-01-chairs-slides-01))
    *   Presented by Peng Liu and Adrian Farrel.
    *   The framework and requirements drafts have been sent to the IESG.
    *   The focus is now on `draft-ietf-cats-metric-definition`.

*   **2.1 CATS-Framework** ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cats-21-cats-framework-00))
    *   Presented by Cheng Li.
    *   The draft passed Working Group Last Call (WGLC).
    *   Comments from the IETF Last Call review (including TSVART, GENART, and SECDIR) have been addressed. 
    *   Special thanks were given to Matt (Cheng Li) for editing revisions 19 through 22.
    *   **Next Step:** Move to IESG last call once final confirmations are received.

*   **2.2. CATS Metrics** ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cats-22-cats-metrics-00))
    *   Presented by Zhuotao Liu regarding `draft-ietf-cats-metric-definition`.
    *   The draft now targets the Standards Track to allow for IANA registration of metrics.
    *   Includes registry entries for Level 1 and Level 2 metrics following templates from RFC 8911 and RFC 8912.
    *   The authors raised a technical question: Can the Service Metric Agent (CSMA) collect communication metrics for the computation of Level 1 or Level 2 metrics?
    *   **Next Step:** Pursue WGLC after the meeting pending list discussion.

### Upcoming Foundation Documents

*   **3.1. CATS OAM Framework** ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cats-slides-for-presentation-draft-fu-cats-oam-framework-00))
    *   Presented by Han Zheng regarding `draft-fu-cats-oam-framework`.
    *   Updated to align with RFC 5706 and RFC 6291.
    *   Introduces a 4-layer OAM model: Service Instance OAM (SIOM) and Service Component OAM (SVCOM).
    *   Adrian Farrel cautioned that the WG should focus on measuring what the CATS system does rather than reinventing network-layer OAM that already exists.

*   **3.2. CATS Security Considerations** ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cats-32-cats-security-considerations-01))
    *   Presented by Du Xiuhua regarding `draft-du-cats-security-considerations`.
    *   Identified risks for CSMA, CNMA, CPS, and CTS, including MITM attacks, false metric injection, and DDoS.
    *   Countermeasures include deploying agents in trusted zones, rate limiting, and using TLS 1.3 for mutual authentication.
    *   Jim Guichard (AD) recommended cross-referencing this work with the security considerations already in the CATS framework document.

*   **3.3. Yang Model for CATS** ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cats-slides-for-draft-yl-cats-data-model-05-00))
    *   Presented by Chen Shung regarding `draft-yl-cats-data-model`.
    *   The model augments RFC 8349 and is protocol-independent.
    *   Defines the Computing Information Base (CCIB) and Network Information Base (CNIB).
    *   The authors requested WG adoption.

*   **3.4. Computing metrics as a service (CMAS)** ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cats-34-computing-metrics-as-a-service-cmas-for-facilitating-traffic-steering-in-cats-framework-draft-zhangb-cats-cmas-02-00))
    *   Presented by Bin Zhang regarding `draft-zhangb-cats-cmas-02`.
    *   Proposes a service-oriented approach using "Globally Available Slots" (GAS) to decouple hardware complexity from network routing.
    *   Guanming questioned how to handle synchronization between CMAS updates and routing protocol convergence.

### Protocol Applicability

*   **4.1. Protocols Applicability for CATS** ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cats-protocols-applicability-for-cats-03))
    *   Presented by Jinyao Hu regarding `draft-hu-cats-protocols-applicability`.
    *   Analyzes existing protocols (BGP-LS, PCEP, BGP FlowSpec) for distributing CATS metrics and steering traffic.
    *   Jeffrey (Zhaohui) Zhang noted that the rate of change for computing state is a critical factor in determining if BGP-LS is a suitable transport.

*   **4.2. BGP Edge Metadata Path Applicability** ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cats-42-bgp-edge-metadata-path-applicability-00))
    *   Presented by Linda Dunbar.
    *   Discussed how BGP metadata (site preference, physical availability) can map to CATS Level 2 metrics.
    *   Emphasized the use of non-transitive attributes to limit metadata distribution to specific domains.

### Specialized Use Cases

*   **5.1. Framework and Applicability of CATS in Optical Transport Networks (OTN)** ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cats-51-framework-and-applicability-of-cats-in-optical-transport-networks-otn-00))
    *   Presented by Cheng Li.
    *   Discussed mapping CATS service instances to optical containers (ODUk/FG-OTN) for deterministic AI workloads.
    *   Adrian Farrel noted this should be framed as "the applicability of OTN to CATS" and suggested coordination with CCAMP and TEAS.

*   **5.2. UONACO** ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cats-52-uonaco-00))
    *   Presented by Han Zheng.
    *   Focuses on lifecycle orchestration for AI workloads over optical networks.
    *   Distinguished from CATS by its focus on pre-provisioning physical/logical links rather than just steering existing traffic.

*   **6.1. IDN and ODSI** ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cats-61-idn-and-odsi-00))
    *   Presented by Haini Wang.
    *   Introduced an Intelligent Delivery Network (IDN) for model deployment and Open Decentralized Scalable Inference (ODSI) for LLMs.

*   **6.2. In-Network Scheduling & Semantic Contract for AI Workloads (Intellinode)** ([Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cats-62-in-network-scheduling-semantic-contract-for-ai-workloads-intellinode-00))
    *   Presented by Haini Wang.
    *   Proposed a "semantic contract" between applications and the network to allow real-time scheduling of AI traffic (e.g., prioritizing gradients over parameter fetches).

## Decisions and Action Items
*   **Action:** Authors of `draft-ietf-cats-metric-definition` to initiate a discussion on the mailing list regarding whether the CSMA should collect communication metrics.
*   **Action:** Authors of `draft-du-cats-security-considerations` to cross-reference and align with the security section in `draft-ietf-cats-framework`.
*   **Action:** Authors of protocol applicability drafts to include analysis on the "rate of change" of metrics and its impact on control plane stability (e.g., BGP churn).

## Next Steps
*   The chairs will evaluate the next set of documents for WG adoption (OAM, Security, and Yang models are top candidates).
*   `draft-ietf-cats-metric-definition` will move toward WGLC following the resolution of the CSMA data collection question.
*   Coordination with the CCAMP working group regarding the optical transport applicability of CATS.